english:
  title: A Discourse on the Crimes of Yi Saek
  author: O Sa-chung
  language: eng
  text: "Yi Saek, Minister of the Gate Below, served our Xuanling well, rising as a Confucian sage to the rank of Chancellor. When Xuanling passed without an heir, the power-seeker Yi Ren-im, desiring to monopolize authority, installed a child king. Yi Saek aided in this counsel and helped establish U upon the throne. When the generals turned their forces toward restoring the Wang clan, the General Cao Min-soo, related to Yi Ren-im by marriage, sought to place his son Chang to continue their selfish schemes. He consulted Yi Saek, who himself had taken Chang to heart, and together they effected his enthronement. Yi Saek's son Jong-hak proclaimed to the royal relatives: \"Though the ministers debated installing a member of the royal house, in the end we placed the crown prince—by our father's doing.\"\n\nWhen Yi Saek returned from the capital, he and Li Chung-in and Kim Sa-an arranged to meet U at Yeohung, yet Yi Saek went ahead alone. What passed in that private audience—whether spoken for the realm or for self—remains unknown. Soon the Heavenly Son decreed: \"Though we made a show of the Wang clan through another surname, this contradicts the time-honored wisdom of the Three Han kingdoms.\" Loyal and righteous men then debated restoring the Wang clan to honor the imperial command. Yet the traitor-minister Byeon An-yeol, seeking unusual merit to seize wealth, conspired with Yi Saek and U's uncle Li Lin, along with Kim Jeo and Jeong Deuk-hu, to welcome U anew and obstruct the restoration of the Wang clan. If one argues that fifteen years of sworn service permits no change of heart, why then abandon five hundred years of the Wang to serve fifteen years of the Shin? \n\nYi Saek served the Wang clan through generations, receiving the boundless grace of King Gongmin. Yet he attached himself to Yi Ren-im and established U, severing the Wang line. When the generals sought to restore the Wang, he bound himself to Cao Min-soo, deposing U to elevate Chang. When loyal ministers moved to recover the Wang throne, he attached to Byeon An-yeol, deposing Chang to welcome U anew. Thus did he become a turncoat to both U and Chang alike.\n\nYet this alone is not the measure of his crime: having served the Wang as ancestral masters, he bowed and scraped before traitors, causing the Wang ancestral line to perish eternally. Such wickedness heaven and earth and the state cannot forgive.\n\nAlas! When Wang Mang usurped the Han, it was accomplished through Zhang Yu. Yet Zhang Yu did not conspire in the plot nor lend his strength directly. Rather, because Zhang Yu stood as a Confucian sage of great repute, when he attached himself to Wang Mang, Mang had nothing to fear, and all the people followed suit. Those who did not attach to Mang became criminals instead. Yet Zhang Yu could not escape the call of Zhu Yun for his execution, nor could he evade posterity's judgment. Yi Saek's attachment to U and Chang, leading the realm into sin, carries a heavier burden still.\n\nMoreover, Yi Saek received honors from Yi Ren-im and enjoyed his wealth. Yet when Yi Ren-im and his cronies Gyeonmi and Heungbang indulged their greed—selling office, releasing the guilty, accepting bribes openly, seizing peasants' fields—Yi Saek spoke not a word against them. As U's tutor, he received repeated rewards, elevating milk-faced youths to high office and placing them in positions of power. When U unleashed his cruelty, slaughtering the innocent, Yi Saek did not correct him. When U recklessly raised armies to invade the great kingdom's borders, sowing endless calamity upon the east, Yi Saek said nothing.\n\nWhen the state sought to correct the private-field system that impoverished the public treasury and harmed the people, Yi Saek, as chief minister, stubbornly refused. Through his son Jong-hak, he spread word among the great families, stirring discontent and slander. All know Li Lin's corruption and weakness, yet Yi Saek curried favor with the royal relatives for his own preservation, recommending Lin to replace himself. Though a Confucian sage, he had the Buddhist canon printed, and the whole realm scrambled to follow suit, each fearing to fall short, corrupting the customs. His son declared to all: \"This was not our father's intention, but the fulfillment of grandfather Gok's wishes\"—thus casting his father into heterodoxy without remorse.\n\nWhen attending Chang's court, his scheme to welcome and enthrone U failed. He then attributed his impeachment to Li Chung-in and withdrew to Jangtdan to await events. When your Highness ascended, he came forth brazenly, accepted the post of Minister of the Gate Below, stood above all officials—showing not a trace of shame. Bending his learning to flatter the age, he fashioned deceit to fish for fame.\n\nI petition that this matter be brought before the relevant ministry: let the crimes of Yi Saek and his son, and of Cao Min-soo, be adjudged, that future generations might learn what befalls ministers who forsake loyalty."
  footnotes:
    - Yi Saek (1328-1396) was a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar who held high office during the late Goryeo and early Joseon periods, serving multiple rulers.
    - The 'Xuanling' (玄陵) refers to King Gongmin of Goryeo.
    - Yi Ren-im was the powerful eunuch who initially wielded control during the interregnum.
    - U and Chang refer to kings U and Chang of Goryeo, Shin dynasty rulers placed by various factions.
    - Zhang Yu was a famous Han Dynasty official whose allegiance to the usurper Wang Mang became a cautionary tale in Chinese history.
    - The 'Three Han' (三韓) refers to the three ancient Korean kingdoms and serves as a reference to Korean national heritage.
